    <div id="page-title-wrapper">
              <h1 class="title">Motion Capture Sequin Dress</h1>
        </div>

    
    </div>
   <!-- /navigation -->

                				        <div id="content">
                    <div id="content-content" class="clear-block"> <div id="node-16983" class="node clear-block">



  <div class="meta">
  
    </div>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="image wrap"><a href="http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/exhibitions/Fashioning-Object/resource/2397" rel="nofollow"><img alt=" Bless, Boudicca, Sandra Backlund" src="../images/Boudicca1.png"></a></div>

<p>Boudicca’s employment of film is often strategic, giving Broach and Kirkby the means to illustrate an idea that might prove less emotive if captured in photography or presented in a traditional fashion show. As its name suggests, the <em>Motion Capture Sequin Dress</em> speaks directly to this idea. Part of Boudicca’s Fragmented Dreams collection, the dress is best understood if viewed in action; when you move your hands across the dress, the sequins flip over, leaving a trail that reflects the motion. To represent this effect, rather than displaying a single image of the dress, the film features a grid of four images, each showing a model with cropped hair at various stages of passing her hands over the dress. The simultaneous, multiple images enhance the mesmerizing effect of the dress.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/exhibitions/Fashioning-Object/resource/2397" rel="nofollow"><strong>See it in motion.</strong></a></p>

<p><hr></p>
<p><sub>Boudicca. <em>Motion Capture Sequin Dress</em>, from the collection <em>Fragmented Dreams</em>, Spring/Summer 2011. Still from film. Courtesy of Boudicca.</sub></p>  </div>

  </div>
